<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-01-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-01-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="1547" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1547">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 819.00/356.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Extracts.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Panama</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-27">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 27, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Minister of Panama at Washington has been instructed to consult the
                            Department of State as to whether the American Government would be
                            willing to supervise the elections. Mendoza tells me that such
                            supervision would appear to be the only way to secure absolute
                            impartiality.</p>
                        <p>The intention of President Arosemena to take leave on February 2 was
                            officially communicated to-day to the Supreme Court.</p>
                        <p>Boyd, the Second Designate, is opposed to Arosemena’s candidacy. The
                            latter has instructed the Minister of Panama to consult the Department
                            as to his constitutional eligibility.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodge.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>